  "prompt": "If I deposit 9 lakhs by cheque into my saving account and withdraws it the same day, will the transaction come under IT notice?",
  "response": "In India, depositing a large amount like 9 lakhs (900,000) in a savings account and then withdrawing it the same day could potentially attract the attention of the Income Tax Department, as such transactions may be considered unusual and could raise questions regarding the source of the funds.\n\nThe Income Tax Department has mechanisms in place to monitor high-value transactions, and banks are required to report certain transactions under the Income Tax Act. If the transaction appears suspicious or if there is no clear explanation regarding the source of the funds, it could lead to further scrutiny or inquiries.\n\nTo avoid any issues:\n\n1. **Source of Funds**: Be prepared to provide documentation or explanation regarding the source of the funds if questioned.\n\n2. **Bank Policies**: Different banks may have different policies about large deposits and withdrawals, and they may flag unusual activity.\n\n3. **Income Tax Return (ITR)**: Ensure that your income tax returns reflect your financial activities accurately, particularly if large transactions are involved.\n\nIn short, while a one-day deposit and withdrawal may not automatically trigger a notice, it could raise flags, and it\u2019s advisable to keep clear documentation regarding the funds involved.",
